The digitized frequency, done by human user for the purpose
			 of finding out the number density

parameters.name: MarkedType
parameters.description:
The type of frequency being digitized. The options are the lower 
			 and upper hybrid frequencies (Flhr, Fuhr) plasma frequency (Fpe), and left and
			 right handed polarized waves (F_L0, F_R0)

parameters.name: Feature
parameters.description:
The visual feature in the spectrogram used to anchor the measurement.
            Defined values follow: 

            1. "bottom"  This denoted the bottom of a feature,usually one extended in
               frequency, hence, this is the low-frequency cutoff

            2. "manual"  The frequency was determined by identifying a feature with
               the cursor -- no algorithm was used.  In practice, the user draws a box
               and a horizontal frequency line is selected for the frequencies to be
               used in that time interval.  Usually, this is used when a cutoff
               frequency or a peak frequency is weak enough that the bottom/top/peak
               algorithm has difficulty selecting a feature.

            3. "manual-diag" Same as manual, except that the selected frequencies lie
               along a diagonal of the drawn box.  This works well when there's a steep
               gradient in frequency but, again, the algorithm has a hard time picking
               out top/bottom/peak.  

            4. "peak"  This is the peak of a narrowband spectral feature.

            5. "top" This denoted the top of a feature -- usually one extended in frequency,
               hence, this is the high-frequency cutoff.

            6. "relabel" This is an option that allows the user to re-define a spectral feature,
              e.g. from fuh to fpe, and is useful when the operator mislabeled the feature to
              begin with and doesn't want to redo the digitization, or if the user 'guesses'
              that this must be one characteristic frequency, but after the tool calculates
              the other frequencies the user realizes a different definition might work better.
              Alone, it doesn't tell you what visual feature was digitized.

parameters.name: Quality
parameters.description:
Currently unused, always set to 'f', may contain a quality rating in future
            versions of the product.

parameters.name: Author
parameters.description: Initials of person who digitized the measurement

parameters.name: Altitude
parameters.description: Altitude above the Jupiter 1 bar atmospheric pressure height

parameters.name: Radius
parameters.description: Radial distance from the center of Jupiter

parameters.name: Mshell
parameters.description: M-shell location of the data points

parameters.name: MagLat
parameters.description: magnetic latitude

parameters.name: Latitude
parameters.description: Jupiter Planetocentric Latitude

parameters.name: Jovigraphic_latitude
parameters.description: latitude in the Jovigraphic coordinate system

parameters.name: Centrifugal_latitude
parameters.description: latitude above Jupiter's centrifugal equator

parameters.name: MLT
parameters.description: Magnetic Local Time

parameters.name: LT
parameters.description: Solar Local Time on Jupiter

parameters.name: WestLong
parameters.description: West Longitude

parameters.name: Ganymede_Radius
parameters.description:
Distance from the barycenter of Ganymede
          at which the in situ observation was made.

parameters.name: Ganymede_Altitude
parameters.description:
Distance from the Juno sub-spacecraft point
          on the Ganymede surface as defined by the NAIF spice
          planetary constants file in the PDS3 dataset 
          "JNO-J/E/SS-SPICE-6-V1.0".

parameters.name: CoRot_X
parameters.description:
The X coordinate in a non inertial frame
          centered at the Ganymede barycenter that rotates once
          for each orbit of Ganymede. The X axis roughly points
          along the moon's velocity vector and can be thought of as
          the direction of plasma flow past the moon.

parameters.name: CoRot_Y
parameters.description:
The Y coordinate in a non inertial frame
          centered at the Ganymede barycenter that rotates once
          for each orbit of Ganymede. The Y axis
          roughly points towards Jupiter.

parameters.name: CoRot_Z
parameters.description:
The Z coordinate in a non inertial frame
          centered at the Ganymede barycenter that rotates once
          for each orbit of Ganymede. The Z axis
          roughly aligns with the moon's orbital angular momentum
          vector.
